Data analysis

fse

We fitted a linear mixed model (estimated using REML and nloptwrap optimizer) to predict fse with group and time_point (formula: fse ~ 1 + group + time_point + group * time_point). The model included login_id as random effect (formula: ~1 | login_id). The model’s total explanatory power is substantial (conditional R2 = 0.64) and the part related to the fixed effects alone (marginal R2) is of 0.04. The model’s intercept, corresponding to group = control and time_point = 1st , is at 17.78 (S.E. = 0.51, p < .001, 95% CI [16.78, 18.78]). Within this model:

  • The effect of group [treatment] is statistically non-significant and positive (beta = 0.19, S.E. = 0.72, p = 0.796, 95% CI [-1.22, 1.59]; Std. beta = 0.05, 95% CI [-0.30, 0.40])
  • The effect of time point [2nd] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -0.57, S.E. = 0.52, p = 0.276, 95% CI [-1.60, 0.46]; Std. beta = -0.14, 95% CI [-0.40, 0.11])
  • The interaction effect of time point [2nd] on group [treatment] is statistically significant and positive (beta = 2.32, S.E. = 0.75, p = 0.002, 95% CI [0.86, 3.78]; Std. beta = 0.58, 95% CI [0.21, 0.94])

Standardized parameters were obtained by fitting the model on a standardized version of the dataset. 95% Confidence Intervals (CIs) and p-values were computed using a Wald normal distribution approximation.
